If `value` needs to a `string`  or an `object` (with shape `{en: &quot;value&quot;, es : &quot;value&quot;}`) you could achieve this using


    Joi.alternatives().try()

The complete code would look like below..

    const joiSchema = Joi.alternatives().try(Joi.string(),
      Joi.object({
        en: Joi.string()
            .required(),
    
        es: Joi.string()
            .required(), 
    }))
    
    const input1 = &quot;Hello&quot;;
    const input2 = {en: &quot;Hi&quot;, es: &quot;Hola&quot;};
    
    
    const joiResponse1 = joiSchema.validate(input1);
    const joiResponse2 = joiSchema.validate(input2);
    console.log(joiResponse1);
    console.log(joiResponse2);

If the value is an object with known keys,  let&#39;s say &quot;en&quot; and &quot;es&quot; and unknown keys whose value has to be string, you could use `Joi.pattern()`.


    const joiSchema = Joi.object({
        en: Joi.string()
            .required(),
    
        es: Joi.string()
            .required(), 
    }).pattern(Joi.string(), Joi.string())
    
    
    const input = {en: &quot;Hi&quot;, es: &quot;Hola&quot;, ab: true};
    
    
    
    const joiResponse = joiSchema.validate(input);
    console.log(joiResponse);

**This is a synchronous call**. The return value of `joiSchema.validate` is an object that has the below structure.

    { error: undefined or validation errors if any,
      value: input value passed,
      then: [Function: then],
      catch: [Function: catch] 
    }

You can check `joiResponse.error` for truthy or falsy to see if there are any validation errors.



I don&#39;t see a similar feature in Yup (Might be I&#39;m wrong as I just skimmed through the doc pages). In my opinion, the best we can do is create a dynamic schema based on the object using `Yup.lazy()`

    let yupSchema = yup.lazy(obj =&gt; {
      return yup.object(
        {
          ...Object.keys(obj).reduce((acc, key) =&gt; {
            acc[key] = yup.string().required()
            return acc;
          }, {}), 
          en: yup.string().required(),
          es: yup.string().required()
        }
      );
    });
    
    //This should fail 
    const input3 = { en: &quot;12&quot;, es: &quot;Hola&quot;, fr: 1.1 };
    yupSchema.validate(input3, {strict: true});



As you said, this returns a promise. So you should handle success and failure using `then` and `catch` clauses of the returned promise.

But there is sync version for this as well, `yupSchema.validateSync`, 
which follows the same syntax as `yupSchema.validate`

As per documentation.

&gt; Runs validatations synchronously if possible and returns the resulting
&gt; value, or throws a ValidationError

    yupSchema.validateSync(input3, {strict: true})

Created a REPL for you to play around with different approach.
https://repl.it/@nithinthampi/UntriedImpracticalShoutcast


Hope this helps!

